Fluorescent protein-LC3ΔG as a negative control

mutant LC3DG, in which the C‑terminal Gly essential for lipidation has been deleted.9 This mutant has defects in the E1‑like reaction mediated by Atg7 and the E2‑like reaction mediated by Atg3, which results in a lack of LC3‑II formation.9‑11 Based on these results and for better versatility, we have generated a set of vectors based on a modified pCXN2 plasmid to express four fluorescent proteins (CFP, GFP, YFP, and HcRed) fused to either wild‑type human LC3 (LC3) or mutant LC3DG in order to monitor autophagy and lipidation‑independent aggregation of LC3 (Fig. 1).12,13 We used human LC3 because its cleavage pattern and all the enzymatic reac‑ tions used for its lipidation are well characterized in vivo and in vitro, and its C terminus after the essential Gly is shorter than that from rat.9‑11,14,15 Fluorescent protein‑LC3DG fusions were expressed in HEK293 cells using these new plasmids (Figs. 2A–C). We first investigated whether these mutant fusions have defects in the E1‑ and E2‑reactions mediated by Atg7 and Atg3 respectively. When an active‑site mutant Atg7C567S was expressed simultaneously with wild‑type fluorescent protein‑LC3 fusions, stable E1‑substrate intermediates were formed (Fig. 2A).10,16 However, when fluorescent protein‑LC3DG fusions were expressed, fewer E1‑substrate intermediates were formed (Fig. 2A). When human Atg3C264S, in which the active site Cys264 has been changed to Ser, was expressed together with wild‑type LC3 fusions and wild‑type human Atg7, stable E2‑substrate intermedi‑ ates were formed (Fig. 2B).11 In contrast, when mutant LC3DG fusions were expressed, only low levels of E2‑substrate intermedi‑ ates were detected (Fig. 2B). These results indicate that fluorescent protein‑LC3DG fusions have defects in E1‑ and E2‑reactions. LC3‑II, a LC3‑phosphatidylethanolamine conjugate, fractionates into the pellet, while LC3‑I remains in the supernatant.14,15,17 The majority of GFP‑LC3DG and HcRed‑LC3DG proteins remained in the supernatant following subcellular fractionation, while their respective wild‑type proteins were pelleted (Fig. 2C). We further investigated the intracellular localization of fluores‑ cent protein‑LC3DG fusions under starvation conditions. After each CFP‑, GFP‑, YFP‑ and HcRed‑LC3DG construct was transiently expressed in CHO cells, the cells were transferred to starvation medium in the presence of E64d and pepstatin A, and incubated for

