Consideration about negative controls for LC3 and expression vectors for four colored fluorescent protein-LC3 negative controls

Negative control for GFP‑LC3

GFP‑LC3 co‑localizes with polyQ72 independent of its lipi‑ dation state. Therefore, we investigated whether LC3DG can be used to recognize lipidation‑indepen‑ dent co‑localization of LC3 with polyQ aggregates (Fig. 4). YFP‑polyQ150 and HcRed‑LC3 or HcRed‑LC3DG were transiently expressed in CHO cells, and YFP and HcRed fluorescence were subse‑ quently visualized. Wild‑type LC3 and HcRed‑LC3DG puncta both co‑localized with YFP‑polyQ150 puncta in CHO cells. Quantification of the fluorescent images indicated that about 60 ± 5% (mean ± SE) of mutant HcRed‑LC3DG puncta co‑local‑ ized with YFP‑polyQ150‑aggregates, and about 68 ± 11% (mean±SE) of wild‑type HcRed‑LC3 puncta co‑localized with YFP‑polyQ150‑aggregates (Fig. 4). The p‑value from the student t‑test between polyQ150‑puncta co‑localized with wild‑type HcRed‑LC3 and HcRed‑LC3DG is greater than 0.5, indicating that there is no statistical difference. Since HcRed‑LC3DG is not lipidated, the colocalization of LC3DG with polyQ150 is independent of lipidation. Therefore, these results suggest that fluorescent protein‑LC3DG fusions are appropriate negative controls for fluo‑ rescent protein‑LC3 in order to determine whether the colocalization of puncta with aggregates is dependent on LC3‑lipidation.
