Figure 3. LC3DG fusion proteins are defective in puncta formation in starvation conditions. Fewer puncta of mutant LC3DG fusion proteins were visible under starvation conditions in the presence of lysosomal protease inhibitors. We transfected each plasmid [pEX-CFPHsLC3WT (a), pEX-GFPHsLC3WT (b), pEX-YFPHsLC3WT (c), pEX-HcRedHsLC3WT (d), pEX-CFPHsLC3DG (e), pEX-GFPHsLC3DG (f), pEX-YFPHsLC3DG (g), pEX-HcRedHsLC3DG (h)] into CHO cells using the lipofection reagent HilyMax (Dojindo, Tokyo, Japan). Following transfection, the CHO cells were cultured in nutrient-rich medium for 48 h, transferred to Krebs-Ringer buffered medium containing E64d (10 mg/ml) and pepstatin A (10 mg/ml), and incubated for an additional 4 h (as described in Ref. 18). The fluorescence within each cell was visualized with a Biozero BZ-8000 microscope (Keyence, Tokyo, Japan) using an appropriate filter set. The numbers of puncta observed were counted, and the relative percentage of puncta is represented graphically, where an average number of wild-type GFP-LC3-puncta is regarded as 100%. p, p-value of student t-test.

es

C op

In the future, it will be advantageous to isolate a cell line that stably expresses fluorescent protein‑LC3. However, when analyzing autophagy in cells that transiently express LC3, usage of mutant LC3DG as a negative control will minimize an overestimation of LC3‑puncta aggregates.
